Skeleton of the grid for a $4\times4$ clue by Aidan Lyon:

$$ \begin{array}{|c|}\hline\end{array} 
   \text{ Ten Thousands} 
   \begin{array}{|c|}\hline\end{array}
   \begin{array}{|c|}\hline\end{array} 
   \text{ (ten's)} 
   \begin{array}{|c|}\hline\end{array}
   \begin{array}{|c|}\hline\end{array} 
   \text{ (ones)} \\
\Downarrow \\
\begin{array}{|c|}\hline\end{array}
 \text{ thousand's digit}  
   \begin{array}{|c|}\hline\end{array}
   \begin{array}{|c|}\hline\end{array} 
   \text{ (hundreds)} \\
   \text{ tens}
\end{array} $$

Assistant: The correct answer is 9000.

Reasoning:

1st Method:

Since we have a thousand's place available to fill, and the first digit is $2$ in this question, we can fill it automatically. Therefore, we have $10×10×10×10=10^4=900$ options for the remaining three digits because there are no restrictions related to the allowed digits.

2nd Method:

If the digits are all the same, then we have $6$ once for every possible hundred's digit. So $10$ times $6$ equals $60$. We just have to multiply $10$ to $60$ once for every possible ten's digit and once for each possible ones digit. This teaches $10×10×10×10=10^4=9000$.

